> Fra diavolo translates literally to "brother devil" in Italian. This devilishly
> spicy tomato sauce is mellowed by sweet sun-dried tomato and succulent shrimp.
> Be sure to sop up all that saucy goodness with plenty of garlicky crostini.

Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Halve @garlic{1%clove}. Halve the @baguette{1%unit}
lengthwise and rub the cut side with the halved garlic. Halve, peel, and thinly
slice the @yellow onion{1%unit}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced). Chop the
@sun-dried tomatoes{1.5%oz}(chopped). Mince all remaining @garlic{1%clove}(minced).
Pick the @oregano{1%sprig}(leaves picked and minced).

Heat @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the
onion, sun-dried tomatoes, and @chili flakes{1/4%teaspoon} (or more!) to the pan
and cook, tossing, until onion is soft, about ~{5%minutes}. Stir in the minced
garlic and oregano and cook for ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add the @diced tomatoes{1%can}, @veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}, and
@water{1/4%cup} to the pan. Reduce the heat to medium-low and simmer for
~{10%minutes}, until sauce has thickened. Season with salt and pepper.

Season the @shrimp{10%ounce} with salt and pepper, then stir into the sauce and
cook for ~{3-4%minutes}, until just pink and opaque.

Meanwhile, drizzle the baguette with @olive oil{1%tablespoon} and season with
salt and pepper. Toast on a #baking sheet{} in the oven for ~{3-4%minutes},
until golden brown and crispy.

Serve the shrimp fra diavolo sprinkled with @chili flakes{} (if you can take the
heat!) and garlic crostini to the side. Buon appetite!